Section 1: Data Description

Number of Observations

  • We can see that the dataset athens_weekends has 2627 observations
  • The dataset athens_weekdays has 2653 observations.
  • However we will make a combined dataset, which will have a total of 5280 observations, however an outlier will be removed making it a total of 5279 observations.

Number of Variables

  • There are 20 variables in the dataset. A variable from the original dataset is removed as it is an outlier, however another variable is created, based on whether the listing is from the weekend dataset or the weekday dataset.

Variable Name and Description

  • realSum: the total price of the Airbnb listing (continuous)
  • room_type: what type of room was offered (categorical)
  • room_shared: whether or not the room is shared or not (categorical)
  • room_private: whether or not the room is private (categorical)
  • person_capacity: the maximum amount of people that can stay in the room (continuous)
  • host_is_superhost: whether or not the host is a superhost (categorical)
  • multi: whether or not the listing is for multiple rooms (categorical)
  • biz: whether or not the listing is for buisness purposes (categorical)
  • cleanliness_rating: the cleanliness rating of the listing (categorical)
  • guest_satisfaction_overall: the overall guest satisfaction rating of the listing (categorical)
  • bedrooms: the number of bedrooms in the listing (categorical)
  • dist: distance from the city center (continuous)
  • metro_dist: distance from the nearest metro station (continuous)
  • attr_index: attraction index of the listing location (categorical)
  • attr_index_norm: normalized attraction index (categorical)
  • rest_index: restaurant index of the listing location (categorical)
  • rest_index_norm: normalized restaurant index (categorical)
  • lng: the longitude of the lisitng (categorical)
  • lat: the latitude of the listing (categorical)
  • is_weekend: 0 if the listing is from the weekday, and 1 if the listing is from the weekend (categorical)

Source and Information

DOI:

Citation: Gydi, K.and . Nawaro. Determinants of Airbnb Prices in European Cities: A Spatial Econometrics Approach (supplementary Material). Zenodo, 13 Jan. 2021, https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4446043.

This research was supported by the National Science Center, Poland with the project number 2017/27/N/HS4/00951

Pre Selection of Variables

The variables that will be dropped include room_type, room_shared, room_private, person_capacity, multi, biz, cleanliness_rating, bedrooms, attr_index, attr_index_norm, rest_index, rest_index_norm, lng, lat and is_weekend. This is because I will be focusing on the price of the listing, distance from the metro and city center, as well as if the host is a superhost or not and whether these factors are associated with guest satisfaction.

Section 2: Scientific Question

  1. The question I wish to answer from my dataset is the association between the guest satisfaction of an Airbnb listing and variables that are related to location (i.e. distance from city center, distance from metro), the price of the Airbnb listing, and whether or not the host is a superhost.
  1. The response variable is variable guest_satisfaction, which is the overall guest satisfaction of the Airbnb listing.
  1. My question is focused on inference, as we are investing the association between the response and explanatory variables. We are not using the explanatory variables to predict what the satisfaction rating of an arbitrary listing may be.

In[3]:
athens_combined <- bind_rows(       # combining the two datasets together
    athens_weekdays |>
        mutate(dayType = "weekday", is_weekend = 0L),
    athens_weekends |>
        mutate(dayType = "weekend", is_weekend = 1L)) |>   #the column ...1 was removed as it 
    select(-`...1`) |>
    arrange(desc(realSum)) |>       #outlier was removed as it was drastically different from rest of data
    slice(-1) |>
    select(realSum, host_is_superhost, guest_satisfaction_overall, dist, metro_dist)

Variable Justification:

  • Variable guest_satisfaction was chosen as it is the response variable we are interested in investigating
  • realSum was chosen as price is a significant factor that is accounted for when selecting an Airbnb
  • host_is_superhost was chosen as a categorical variable as we are interested in observing and how it is associated with guest satisfaction

Visualization Interpretation:

  1. These plots are relevant in answering my question as it plots Guest Satisfaction vs Price of Listing, with the colours representing if they are a superhost or not. These two plots allow us to get a general understanding of how price and superhost status may play a role in the rating the listing may recieve.
  2. From the visualizations, we can see that for both weekday and weekend listings, the majority of the lisings seems to recieve ratings between 80 and 100, and are below 500 Euros. We can also see that being a superhost seems to have a noticable association with the guest satisfaction overall as the majoirty of the superhost listings are around 90-100 while there are a significant amount of non superhost listings lower.
  3. From the plot, I learned that a higher price may have a small association with the guest satisfaction, while being a superhost seems to have a more apparent association with guest satisfaction. I also learned that there does not seem to be a big difference between the weekday and weekend listing, which may be explained by the two sharing a number of points.

Section 4: Method and Plan

The method I propose to answer my scientific question is multiple linear regression with an additive model using guest_satisfaction_overall as the outcome and dist, metro_dist, realSum and host_is_superhost as the covariates. The choice to use an additive model is due to the fact that our research question is looking at the individual associations between the covariates and guest satisfaction. Although our response variable, guest_satisfaction_overall is on a 0-100 scale, we will treat it as a continuous response variable as there are many levels and it behaves similarly to a numeric score. Thus the decision to use MLR is appropriate as we are using multiple explanatory variables to understand how they are associated with the average guest satisfaction of an Airbnb listing. To use the MLR model, we will have to assume LINE: linear relation between the response and predictors, errors are independent, conditional distribution of the error terms are normal and the variance of the error terms are equal. Potential limitations are that the model may not account for the range restriction as the response variable is bounded from 0-100. Another limitation is that the model doesn't account for several confounders which weren't observed by the dataset, with examples including amenities, safety, etc.

    mutate_if(is.numeric, round, 3)

Interpreting the table above, we see that being a superhost is associated with a higher guest satisfaction, with listings rated 4.268 units higher on average while holding price and location constant. We can also see that realSum is statistically significant because its p-value is very small, suggesting that more expensive listings are associated with higher ratings. The variables dist and metro_dist are not statistically significant as the p-values are greater than 0.1, meaning there is no strong evidence that the location of an airbnb is associated with guest satisfaction. A limitation of this model is that there may be hidden covariates that were not observed in the dataset such as amenities, which may impact the ratings observed.
